\begin_layout Subsection
Histone variants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to histone tail modifications, chromatin can be modified by
 the incorporation of histone variants.
 Canonical core histone genes are found in clustered repeat arrays within
 the genome, are transcribed during replication and are extremely tightly
 conserved between species.
 Histone variants are found as single genes spread through the genome, and
 are subject to far greater diversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Talbert2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CENP-A is a human variant of histone H3 which replaces the canonical histone
 in centromeric heterochromatin.
 It is a key factor in the establishment of the centromeres and kinetochores
 required for mitosis.
 The histone variant is incorporated with the help of a number of chaperone
 proteins, including HJURP, after replication of DNA has finished 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dunleavy2009,Foltz2009"

\end_inset

.
 CENP-A is essential for the formation of centromeres.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another frequent histone variant found in humans is H3.3, which differs from
 canonical H3 by just four amino acids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Talbert2010"

\end_inset

.
 This histone variant is found within transcribed genes, promoters and regulator
y elements, and is thought to be laid down during transcriptional elongation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schwartz2005"

\end_inset

.
 Nucleosomes containing H3.3 appear to be less stable than canonical nucleosomes,
 with a high turnover of H3.3 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schwartz2005"

\end_inset

.
 It is possible that this increased turnover of the nucleosomal components
 helps to keep the chromatin open and accessible to the transcriptional
 machinery 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Talbert2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

