\begin_layout Section
Chromosome Territories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interphase nucleus is a highly structured organelle.
 As chromosomes decondense after metaphase they retain some degree of structure,
 forming 
\emph on
chromosome territories
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CT"
description "Chromosome territory"

\end_inset

CTs) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer2001"

\end_inset

.
 Circumstantial evidence for such interphase organisation of the chromosomes
 has existed for a long time, first suggested by Carl Rabl in 1885 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rabl1885"

\end_inset

.
 Oberservations by Stack 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 using microscopy with giemsa-band staining suggested that chromosomes retained
 some degree of organisation during interphase 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stack1977"

\end_inset

, and in 1982 Cremer 
\emph on
et al., 
\emph default
showed that interphase chromosomes exist in 'territories' by studying the
 pattern of DNA damage in metaphase chromosomes after spot irradiation in
 during interphase 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer1982"

\end_inset

.
 The subsequent development of 'chromosome paints', a method to visualise
 entire- or part- chromosomes with (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FISH"
description "Fluorescence in-situ hybridisation"

\end_inset

FISH), confirmed these findings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schardin1985a,Manuelidis1985"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As FISH techniques have developed, so too has the detail with which CT organisat
ion can be studied.
 Several groups have shown that chromosome territory position within the
 nucleus is not random and correlates with chromosome size 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sun2000,Cremer2001b"

\end_inset

, gene-density 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer2001b,Croft1999"

\end_inset

 and replication timing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Visser1998"

\end_inset

: those near the centre of the nucleus tend to be gene-rich, early replicating
 and small.
 
