\begin_layout Section
Transcription factories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One nuclear subcompartment which has come to light within the past twenty
 years is the 
\emph on
transcription factory
\emph default
, foci of hyper-phosphorylated RNA Polymerase II spread throughout the nucleus.
 The majority of geneic transcription appears to take place at transcription
 factories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jackson1993a,Osborne2004,Eskiw2008a"

\end_inset

, challenging the classical model of transcription found in many text books.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 'transcription factories' was coined by Jackson 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 in 1993.
 Fluorescence microscopy was used to label the incorporation of bromouridine
 triphosphate (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "BrUTP"
description "Bromouridine triphosphate"

\end_inset

BrUTP) into nascent RNA; discrete foci of nascent transcription could be
 seen within the nucleus which did not form in the presence of the RNA Polymeras
e II inhibitor Î±-amanitin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jackson1993a"

\end_inset

.
 Further studies showed that these foci contain RNA Polymerase II along
 with many other components required for transcription 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Iborra1996,Grande1997"

\end_inset

.
 An ultrastructural study by Eskiw 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 used correlative microscopy with both electron spectroscopic imaging (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ESI"
description "Electron spectroscopic imaging"

\end_inset

ESI) and fluorescence microscopy to study nuclei sections.
 ESI can distinguish nitrogen and phosphorous atoms without labelling, and
 fluorescence light microscopy can visualise transcription through labelling
 BrUTP in nascent transcripts.
 The authors found that nascent RNA is almost always associated with the
 surface of large nitrogen-rich protein structures with a diameter of ~87
 nm, comparable in size to that of a transcription factory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Eskiw2008a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

